        "text": "Diverse Representations\n\nvery little\n\nAlmost all characters are White men. The story uses a White savior narrative, showing aristocratic members of the English parliament—William Wilberforce and William Pitt—suffering for the cause of abolition, while Black activists and women are sidelined. Black abolitionist Olaudah Equiano (Senegalese actor/musician Youssou N'Dour) is reduced to a minor, tokenized role that's mostly silent. He exists as a symbol of Black trauma, dramatically revealing his scarred chest to shock a table of White people or stoically crying—finally becoming a gravestone for a White character to visit years in the future. Wilberforce's wife, Barbara, has no character development; she's seen only adoring, supporting, and inspiring her husband before becoming the mother of his children. A double amputee and unhoused man briefly appears to make the rich and nondisabled Wilberforce look kind, as he gives money. But the film does demonstrate the realities of how to create lasting social change, showing years of perseverance by a coalition of activists.\n\nDid we miss something on diversity? Suggest an update.\n\nParents need to know that Amazing Grace is a historical drama that tells the story of William Wilberforce (Ioan Gruffudd), a British abolitionist and politician in the late 1700s and early 1800s. Wilberforce and other supporting characters demonstrate integrity, courage, and perseverance. Characters describe slavery in direct, no-holds-barred language, including mention of women being hung by their ankles and raped onboard ships, with further detail on the inhumane living conditions of enslaved people. There's very little on-screen violence, though a formerly enslaved man reveals a scarred brand on his chest and a horse is beaten in an early scene. Men smoke pipes, and several characters drink liquor, both at parties and alone. Wilberforce takes laudanum to treat a medical condition. Language includes \"ass,\" \"hell,\" and \"damn,\" and an overtly racist White character uses the \"N\" word a couple of times. Though the film demonstrates the strong willpower and coalition-building needed to make great social change, Amazing Grace easily falls into a White savior narrative as Black characters and women are sidelined in favor of upper-class White men's roles in the abolition of slavery in Britain. To stay in the loop on more movies like this, you can sign up for weekly Family Movie Night emails."
